### 546. Installing Docker on macOS
This note will provide detailed steps and instructions to install Docker and signup for a DockerHub account on  **macOS**. We will need a DockerHub account so that we can pull images and push the images we will build.

1.  **Register for a DockerHub account**
    Visit the link below to register for a DockerHub account (this is free)
    
    [https://hub.docker.com/signup](https://hub.docker.com/signup)
    
2.  **Navigate to the Docker Desktop installation page**
    [https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/)
    
3.  **Select your Chip**
    Click the button that corresponds with the chip of your computer. If you have an M1 or M2 machine, you will need to click the Mac with Apple Chip button. Everyone else will need to click the Mac with Intel Chip button.
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-31-46453354fd271349326a63385a314e49.png)
    
4.  **Double-click the Docker.dmg file in your Downloads**
    
5.  **Drag and drop the Docker icon to the Applications folder**
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-31-6599a72428100d0ebd6b590851ca1db4.png)
    
6.  **Go to Applications and double-click click the Docker icon:**
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-31-53beb74ca984c1d63f2d7f3bc7329bc2.png)
    
7.  **Select "Open" in the "Are you Sure you want to open it" prompt**
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-2f0b32e026422f3bfcdd93eac0d8c94e.png)
    
8.  **Click "Accept" to the Service Agreement**
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-2662a3aa6de3edf6ebb88b21143abff3.png)
9.  **Click "OK" to "Docker Desktop needs privileged access" prompt**
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-97c392f41eefa6133d29ef512279f213.png)
    
10.  **Enter your computer's username and password to install the helper**
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-ac38b06ec8fe18bdc7b4991375314cb9.png)
    
11.  **Docker Desktop will launch for the first time**
    
    If the installation was successful, Docker Desktop will launch and present you with a tutorial. You are free to skip this.
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-2ed3838d59828ffa1d1edd4cdef43108.png)
    
12.  **Check that Docker is working**
    
    Open your Terminal application and run the  `docker`  command. If all is well you should see some helpful instructions in the output similar to below.
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-07_21-55-32-5f32d6beb5982b425bec15cf8e6ec848.png)
    
13.  **Log in to Docker**
    
    Using your Terminal Application run the  `docker login`  command. You will be prompted to enter the Username and password (or your Personal Access Token) you created in step #1 when registering for a DockerHub account.
    
    ![](https://img-b.udemycdn.com/redactor/raw/article_lecture/2022-09-08_16-21-18-04a671db74a8ebdcf48af0b6bc2ddcd9.png)
    
    Once you see  **Login Succeeded**, the setup is complete and you are free to continue to the next lecture.

### 550. But Really... What's a Container?
**![](https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/q4uGcjowgK0RnBWje-WpK0A_Xsgi6UE-U1FSbbcRPWJWx3R5jUl4rrb7vB-vcirQfcRBOFq_skjH10mf5mL_OqPDb-Ta48e_5rFLLXcy65Dq_VwNZnRkMN2c871agZyt6glVx7HFebFjVEuQ8nzV8bY)**
* kernel governs access between programs running on computer to physical hardware connected to computer
* running programs interacts with kernel through system calls
**![](https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/HPZx2uorJAZDso_b2a9pSZ9TzzASj_Gi3qToXWaW1CTHCwcNFovojLX7qR-aTQK4XAeHZ9TC2PsyPYv-lsw-4KjFfBL9UXx_etF_jKJ_ykcVPcmNmPCg8zpV7b0sjgpQ1tOluN1PsXGh9bM9ut7ECMI)**
* imagine crazy world where we need python 2/3 and system can only have one python
**![](https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/7ClwJt-DsfEaJWKhe8k3J6DgWdfyj9XexHMNvSjlJVYYT-D-ykn_U7fZioIdTxFGK2ex0dRZfzFtxeGFk9QR0PgNUNligaNozpD2dbV0wEo5sGFSKEZ_HRtxlg2HRESHNKnRqHO7sZ4gfU8tjcgcJos)**
* one way to solve issue is to use namespacing, OS feature
* segment out hardware resources
* whenever we have system call, kernel can redirect to right segment

**![](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/CaJBoyUZf8XZb0bQj2ePumEmTqbK1MXSJsatV691kF_ADx-pAJtAamnm5qwujnscc61OdPOUzo2c-c-SI-r022Z4-F4YDtA5XcWWwT7ieb7JINsjJ2_nXBcmv3PL8E5MpEp1YcPg7jg5IDXBbleuGJY)**
* namspacing
	* isolating resources per process (or group of processes
	* not only used for hardware, also software 
* control groups (cgroups)
	* limit **amount** of resources used per process

**![](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/UHZkxxrD9YtpGlcntWb9t82UZ47OwNcCQAsC2eYfUXeibYqk4nhIxP1By44cM-q-XVvRy8KuYu7JaTOduyWbCc9cH8ZD0gtXFRlxV9egU9Sz6q41nXh43-oiCCxs8FLYBwV4IsPaZEWS4alctDtAG_M)**
**![](https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/ZQWoQ8B2r2uJLaEQLZZcEH63-I-2iZlW10eWlIEc1AocwD1EQJ1HSqM_YBxOHZK2hZdse68AnMChl5Vv1NcGuVebW_FkxQOI1ZRMTWbYerEXqpo6rW5UWNzrpmG7bLlglP760a1DBXpZKeG7iyXlerM)**
* image is snapshot of fs, and startup command
* use portion of hardware to install snapshot
* run startup
* "**Docker uses namespaces to provide the isolated workspace called the container**"

### 557. Removing Stopped Containers
* `docker system prune`

	* all networks not used by at least one computer
	* all dangling images

* resets docker ps --all, saves disk space, but removes images

### 559. Stopping Containers
* ping command with docker start - how to stop? didn't pass -i for interactive
* `docker stop <container id>`
	* sends SIGTERM, tells it to stop on its own time
	* lets it shut down and do clean up
	* similar to `kill [id]` in linux https://komodor.com/learn/sigterm-signal-15-exit-code-143-linux-graceful-termination/#:~:text=How%20Can%20You%20Send%20SIGTERM%20to%20a%20Process%20in%20Linux%3F&text=By%20default%2C%20the%20kill%20command,which%20lists%20all%20running%20processes.
		* SIGKILL is `kill -9 [id]`
* `docker kill <container id>`
	* SIGKILL
**![](https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/5D2ZMZC8uiOW2rlgcUzHfoNaP-M36-v-_7ANO-Qvhu8vbaOsRMHh44TANs7jYt93uJfk1PKmGLTNL05sWoZWeBuGMX3kG3BezXPDDysT9B3KiENZM12NcyjH0lixX0jLoRc-Q8zxCn-6UGToFh4YBq4)**
* stop - if image doesn't shut in 10s, switch to kill
* ping command doesn't properly respond to SIGTERM
* ps - list jobs snapshot, top - list curr jobs, jobs - list jobs in current shell, kill, fg, bg

### 567. Buildkit for Docker Desktop
Most students who have the most recent versions of Docker will now have  **Buildkit**  enabled by default. If so, you will notice a slightly different output in your terminal when building from a Dockerfile.

The main difference for students will be the final step in the build process. As shown in the lecture the last step would say:
```
1.  ---> fc60771eaa08
2.  Successfully  Built fc60771eaa08
```
Now, with Buildkit, the final step would say:
```
1.    =>  => exporting layers 
2.  0.0s  =>  => writing image sha256:ee59c34ada9890ca09145cc88ccb25d32b677fc3b61e921 0.0s
```
Both  **_fc60771eaa08_** _and_ **_ee59c34ada9890ca09145cc88ccb25d32b677fc3b61e921_** are the resulting image ID's that you would use to run a container.
eg:
4.  docker run fc60771eaa08
or
5.  docker run ee59c34ada9890ca09145cc88ccb25d32b677fc3b61e921

#### **Disabling Buildkit to match course output**
If you wish to disable the Buildkit feature so that you can more accurately follow along with the course, do the following:
1.  Click the Docker Icon in the system tray (Windows) or menu bar (macOS)
2.  Select  **Preferences**
3.  Select  **Docker Engine**
4.  Change buildkit from  **true**  to  **false**
```
    1.  {
    2.    "features":  {
    3.    "buildkit":  false
    4.    },
    5.    "experimental":  false
    6.  }
```
5.  Apply and Restart.
    
#### **Buildkit Features and Documentation**
If you want to learn more about features Buildkit has to offer, please check out the following pages:
[https://docs.docker.com/develop/develop-images/build_enhancements/](https://docs.docker.com/develop/develop-images/build_enhancements/)
[https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/build/#specifying-external-cache-sources](https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/build/#specifying-external-cache-sources)
[https://www.docker.com/blog/advanced-dockerfiles-faster-builds-and-smaller-images-using-buildkit-and-multistage-builds/](https://www.docker.com/blog/advanced-dockerfiles-faster-builds-and-smaller-images-using-buildkit-and-multistage-builds/)


### 568. Building a Dockerfile
* goal - create an image that runs redis-server
* create `Dockerfile`, no extension
```
# Use an existing docker image as a base
FROM alpine

# Download and install a depedency
RUN apk add --update redis

# Tell the image what to do when it starts as a container
CMD ["redis-server"]
```
* `docker build .`
* `docker run [id]`

### 569. Dockerfile Teardown
* `FROM alpine`
	* specify docker image base
* `run apk add --update redis`
	* execute some command while preparing our custom image
* `cmd ["redis-server"]`
	* specifies what should be executed when our image is used to start new container
* first word, instruction telling docker server what to do, second argument to instruction

	* execute chrome.exe } command to run on startup
* FROM alpine
	* initial OS/ starting image
* why use alpine as a base image?
	* why do you use windows MacOS or Ubuntu?

	* has programs useful run running redis

		* apache package 

### 571. The Build Process in Detail
* dockerfile -> docker client -> docker server -> usable image!
* ^ configuration to define how our container should behave
* `docker build .` -> giving dockerfile to cli
* one step for each line of docker file
* no intermediate container for step 1
* each step uses image from previous step


**![](data:image/png;base64,)**
* running commands as the process in container
* doesn't run the last command
* take snapshot, save image

### 572. A Brief Recap
* `FROM alpine`
	* download alpine
* `RUN apk add --update redis`
	* get image from prev step
	* create a container out of it -> container!
	* run `RUN apk add --update redis` in it-> container! with modified FS
	* take snapshot of container's FS -> FS snapshot
	* shut down tem container
	* get image ready for next instruction
* `CMD ["redis-server]`
	* get image from last step
	* create a container out of it -> container!
	* tell container it should run `redis-server` when started -> container! with modified primary command
	* shut down that temp container
	* get image ready for next instruction
* no more steps!
* output is the image generated from previous step

### 573. Rebuilds with Cache
* add `RUN apk add --update gcc`
	* doesn't do anything just adding new step for instructional purposes
* when I run it, it doesn't list CMD (never did, maybe docker updated since vid)
* caches old step  `RUN apk add --update gcc`
* reordering messes up cache, rerun from changed steps down
* put changes as far down as possible to reduce time to rebuild image

### 574. Tagging an Image
* `docker run [id]` kind of a pain
* tagging an image
	* `docker build -t exzack/redis:latest .`
		* `-t exzack/redis:latest`  tags the image
			* `[dockerid]/[repo/projectname]:[version]`
		* . - specifies the directory of files/folders to use for the build
* other simplified names redis, busybox, hello-world
	* those are community images - created by people in community and open-source for popular use
* `docker run exzack/redis` don't need to put version, use latest by default
* whole process is tagging the image, but technically only the version number at end is tag, everything before is repo/project name

### 576. Manual Image Generation with Docker Commit
* image -> container -> image
	* |v->container
* can we run container from image, but can also create image from container (manually doing what the dockerfile does)
* `docker run -it alpine sh`
* `apk add --update redis`
* docker ps (to get ID)
* `docker commit -c 'CMD ["redis-server"]' b98e71325442`
	* can also use short start of id (assumed unique)
* don't really want to do this in practice, want to use dockerfile for reproducibility

### 579. A Few Planned Errors
* node js apps
	* have to install dependencies before running the app
		* `npm install` -> assumes npm is installed
	* have to run a command to start the server
		* `npm start` -> assume npm is installed
* template (similar to redis)
	* specify base image -> `FROM alpine` -> `FROM alpine`
	* run commands to install additional programs -> `RUN apk add --update redis` -> `run npm install`
	* specify a command to run on container startup -> `CMD ["redis-server"]` -> `CMD ["npm", "start"]`
* `docker build .` -> npm not found

### 580. Required Node Base Image Version
In the upcoming lecture, we will be adding a Node base image to our Dockerfile.  **To properly follow along with the lectures, please add this specific version:**

Change this:
`FROM node:alpine`
to this:
`FROM node:14-alpine`

#### **If you do not specify a Node version**

If you do not specify a version, you will meet a number of errors caused by changes in the newest versions of Node:

_npm ERR! idealTree already exists_

This can be resolved by adding a WORKDIR right after the FROM instruction: (we will be adding this in the  [Specifying a Working Directory](https://www.udemy.com/course/docker-and-kubernetes-the-complete-guide/learn/lecture/11436960#questions)  lecture anyway):  
```
1.  FROM node:alpine
2.  WORKDIR /usr/app
```

### 583. Copying Build Files

* still can't visit port

### 584. Container Port Forwarding
* making request to local machine at port 8080
* by default no traffic coming to local computer routed to container which has isolated set of ports that can receive traffic
* set up explicit port mapping 
* this is for incoming requests, container can make requests to outside (eg npm install)
* change way we start container (docker run command) - not docker file
* docker run with port mapping
	* `docker run -p 8080:8080 <image id>`
		* incoming request on local host:port inside container
		* sourcing mapping from->to don't need to be the same
			* will be done frequently in production apps?
* `docker run  -p 5000:8080 exzack/simpleweb`
* can change target port as well, but also change port in application itself

### 585. Specifying a Working Directory
* `docker run -it exzack/simpleweb sh`
* placed into root directory - bad practice
	* can have file/folder conflicts with default system
	* why we run `WORKDIR /usr/app`
		* any following command will be executed relative to this path in the container
* doesn't matter much, but usr file good to place
* `exit`
* everything reran from scratch since we add WORKDIR command near top
	* affects not just DOCKERFILE, but also commands later with exec command

### 586. Unnecessary Rebuilds
* `docker run -p 8080:8080 exzack/simpleweb`
* image is a snapshot
* changes to local file to update image -> needs additional fancy configuration - will do next app
* what will we need to do here? rebuild container
* copied all files again, don't need to run NPM install again? since only changed source code files, not package.json
